@page "/components/state-extensions"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@inherits PageBase

@*
    Auth / Culture / Workspace / Catalog are already exposed by ExtensionsBase as
    `Authenticated` / `Culture` / `Workspace` / `Catalog` protected properties — no
    @inject needed (and re-injecting them would shadow the base hooks that subscribe
    to OnChange for auto re-render).
*@

<h1>State extensions — prerender ↔ interactive bridge</h1>

<p>
    Blazor renders interactive pages twice — once on the server (SSR / prerender) and
    again after the circuit is established. Identity, organisation, project and culture
    are all <em>request-scoped</em> on the server but vanish when the circuit reconnects.
    The four <code>Zonit*Extension</code> components persist that state through
    <code>PersistentComponentState</code> so the second render sees exactly what the
    first one saw — no flicker, no extra round-trip, no JSInterop dance.
</p>

<p class="muted">
    <code>UseWebsite&lt;App&gt;()</code> already injects these into <code>App.razor</code>;
    the page below just <em>reads</em> the providers they hydrate, so reloading shows the
    same values immediately on both render passes.
</p>

<section class="card">
    <h2>ZonitIdentityExtension → IAuthenticatedProvider</h2>
    @if (!Authenticated.Current.HasValue)
    {
        <p class="muted">Anonymous — log in via <a href="/login">/login</a>.</p>
    }
    else
    {
        <pre>Authenticated.Current.Id    -> @Authenticated.Current.Id
Authenticated.Current.Name  -> @Authenticated.Current.Name.Value
Authenticated.Current.Roles -> @string.Join(", ", Authenticated.Current.Roles.Select(r => r.Value))</pre>
    }
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>ZonitCulturesExtension → ICultureProvider</h2>
    <pre>Culture.Current.Value         -> @Culture.Current.Value
Culture.Current.NativeName    -> @Culture.Current.NativeName</pre>
    <p class="muted">
        Switch the culture in the top-bar — both the prerender and the interactive
        circuit will land on the value you picked, persisted via this extension.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>ZonitOrganizationsExtension → IWorkspaceProvider</h2>
    @if (!Workspace.Organization.HasValue)
    {
        <p class="muted">No active organisation. Pick one at <a href="/organizations">/organizations</a>.</p>
    }
    else
    {
        <pre>Workspace.Organization.Id    -> @Workspace.Organization.Id
Workspace.Organization.Name  -> @Workspace.Organization.Name.Value</pre>
    }
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>ZonitProjectsExtension → ICatalogProvider</h2>
    @if (!Catalog.Project.HasValue)
    {
        <p class="muted">No active project. Pick one at <a href="/projects">/projects</a>.</p>
    }
    else
    {
        <pre>Catalog.Project.Id    -> @Catalog.Project.Id
Catalog.Project.Name  -> @Catalog.Project.Name.Value
Catalog.Visible.Length-> @Catalog.Visible.Length</pre>
    }
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>How they wire up</h2>
    <p>
        These four components are mounted by <code>UseWebsite&lt;App&gt;()</code> via the
        source-generated <code>HeadOutlet</code>-style insertion. You only see them in
        DOM as <code>&lt;persistent-component-state&gt;</code> entries in the prerender
        markup — <em>no visible UI</em>. The pattern works for any request-scoped state:
        write your own <code>Zonit*Extension</code> against
        <code>PersistentComponentState.PersistAsJson(JsonTypeInfo, …)</code> and you stay
        AOT-safe (see <code>OrganizationsStateJsonContext.cs</code> for the recipe).
    </p>
</section>
